The old farmer said, "When you're driving down a country road and you come across a fence post with a tortoise balanced on top, that's a post tortoise." The old farmer saw the puzzled look on the doctor's face so he continued to explain. status_message: History matters. Memorial Day was first celebrated by newly free Black Americans in Charleston, South Carolina at the end of the Civil War. To dedicate the cemetery, the community organized a parade, described in a New York Tribune account as "a procession of friends and mourners as South Carolina and the United States never saw before." At the front of the parade were Black children, laden with roses and singing "John Brown's Body".

EDITED TO SAY: The language we used in this post is problematic for a few reasons, but rather than take it down, we wanted to correct it here so that everyone else could learn the lesson we did, and so that we could own our mistake rather than hiding it. So here's where we messed up:

People who identify as transgender should never be described as "transgendered," as it adds unnecessary length to the word and turns an adjective into a noun, adding a level of distance that comes across as disrespectful. Same goes for "a transgender" or "a group of transgenders," or any other case of turning the adjective "transgender" into a noun. Imagine someone describing a gay man as "the gayed" or "a gay." Not great. It makes it sound like something that has been done to a person, rather than a description of an aspect of who they are.

And adding a "the" to the phrase "the transgendered" - instead of "transgender people" - doubles that distancing effect, making this meme a double whammy of incorrect grammar and distancing language. As one person wrote, "I feel like Republicans use that language passive aggressively to try to dismiss trans people," and that's not a good look on us. 

Obviously, no one group of people who share an identity are a hive mind, and there are some transgender people - especially older folks - who use or don't mind "transgendered," so we're not trying to speak for everyone here. Here's one place to start learning about some generally agreed-upon language for talking about people who don't identify as cisgender: http://www.transpride.ca/trans-media-reference.htm

We're grateful to the folks in the comments who pointed out our mistake, and to our friends at home who generously used their time to give us some schooling on this today. Please continue to let us know when we're fuckin' up, and we'll continue working hard not to fuck up. Thank you all!

status_message:
The math might surprise you.

Public tuition in the United States is nearly $70 billion. Pell grants the federal government already uses bring that down to about $40 billion -- that's how much it would cost to make tuition at public universities in the United States free. 

That's 7.5% of the massive $526 billion military budget.

Utah's "houses for homeless" program essentially eradicated homelessness in the state, at an annual cost of $10,000-$12,000 per person. There are 610,000 homeless people in the United States. It'd cost 7.32 billion to house them all.

So let's recap. 10% of $526 billion is $52.6 billion. After Pell grants, the cost of public tuition in the US would be only $40 billion. That, in addition to the cost of providing housing, would be $47.32 billion, considerably less than 10% of the military budget. 

It's not about money.

It's about priorities.
